Most journalists would probably like to forget about the media coverage of =
the 2016 campaign, but unfortunately, the drama of that year is burned into=
 all of our brains like an acid flashback. I have one particularly vivid me=
mory I return to from time to time. I was in my hotel room in St. Louis on =
the morning of the second presidential debate between Hillary Clinton and D=
onald Trump. MSNBC was on in the background, and I turned to watch Andrea M=
itchell interview Clinton=E2=80=99s campaign manager, Robby Mook. It was th=
e same day that Trump held a Facebook Live press conference with three of t=
he women who had accused Bill Clinton of sexual misconduct back in the =E2=
=80=9990s=E2=80=94Juanita Broaddrick, Paula Jones, Kathleen Willey=E2=80=94=
and Kathy
Shelton, a sexual assault victim whose rapist was defended by Hillary Clint=
on more than 40 years ago. The four women, Trump announced, would be attend=
ing that night=E2=80=99s debate.

Mitchell asked Mook about this ploy, which was all over the news. =E2=80=9C=
This has been reported many times,=E2=80=9D he said calmly. =E2=80=9CObviou=
sly, the Clintons had a tough time in their marriage 20 years ago. This was=
 litigated a lot, and I don=E2=80=99t think voters are interested in litiga=
ting it again.=E2=80=9D

My gut response was that Mook was half right. The Clinton scandals of yeste=
ryear did feel like old news. But I also figured that a lot of boomers had =
never forgotten about Bill=E2=80=99s sliminess back in the day, and that Tr=
ump=E2=80=99s gambit might remind them they didn=E2=80=99t want the Clinton=
s anywhere near the White House again.

What I didn=E2=80=99t account for, being the high-information political kno=
w-it-all that I am, was that a lot of younger voters probably had no idea
about the Clinton-era sex scandals. For them, it was new information=E2=80=
=94and possibly yet another excuse to stay home on Election Day rather than=
 vote for Hillary. In hindsight, this gimmick was effective for the Trump c=
ampaign.

As Chuck Klosterman wrote in his excellent history The Nineties, even thoug=
h Bill Clinton left office with one of the highest approval ratings in mode=
rn history, today he is remembered as =E2=80=9Can irreconcilable villain am=
ong young people (and particularly young women) who have little or no memor=
y of Clinton=E2=80=99s time in office.=E2=80=9D For younger millennials and=
 especially Gen Z, who came of age during the #MeToo era, his sexual transg=
ressions eclipse his administration=E2=80=99s achievements.

I thought about all this last week after seeing a poll from a newish Democr=
atic outfit called Blueprint, whose purported mission is =E2=80=9Cto take a=
 sober, detailed look at what Democrats need to do to win in 2024.=E2=80=9D=
 The report is
titled Trumpnesia, and the results are ominous for Democrats who are worrie=
d about getting Gen Z to vote for Biden. It turns out that not only do many=
 young and first-time voters not really remember the chaos of the Trump yea=
rs, but they don=E2=80=99t really care that much when presented with exampl=
es of his most inflammatory rhetoric.

The Biden Lesson

No matter your partisan affiliation, you likely remember the scandals that =
defined Trump=E2=80=99s first campaign for president and his presidency: th=
e Muslim ban; the Access Hollywood tape; the claims that Mexican migrants a=
re murderers and rapists; the dismissal of servicemen who died in war as =
=E2=80=9Closers=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csuckers.=E2=80=9D That story about Tr=
ump calling Haiti and African nations =E2=80=9Cshithole countries.=E2=80=9D=
 And so on. These low points will be in Trump=E2=80=99s obituary. MSNBC has=
 been talking about them in primetime for almost a decade.

But in a survey of registered voters ( https://blueprint2024.com/analysis/t=
rump-statements-youth-poll/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUB=
SCRIBERS+%286%2F10%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSC=
RIBERS+%286%2F6%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&=
utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) between
the ages of 18 and 30, Blueprint found that multitudes of young people in A=
merica have never even heard of these Trump comments. Only 42 percent of yo=
ung voters were aware of Trump disparaging John McCain as =E2=80=9Cnot a wa=
r hero=E2=80=9D; the same low percentage had heard of Trump=E2=80=99s propo=
sal for the =E2=80=9Ctotal and complete shutdown of Muslims entering the Un=
ited States.=E2=80=9D Likewise, a majority of young voters professed utter =
ignorance over Trump=E2=80=99s statement that there were =E2=80=9Cvery fine=
 people on both sides=E2=80=9D of the 2017 white supremacist march in Charl=
ottesville, a moment the Biden campaign highlighted in a digital ad back in=
 March.

=E2=80=9CThe whole Trumpnesia lesson, to me, isn=E2=80=99t to go out and re=
mind everyone of this stuff,=E2=80=9D said Evan Ross Smith, the lead pollst=
er for Blueprint. =E2=80=9CThe lesson is that you can=E2=80=99t rely on the=
se voters having this bedrock understanding of Trump as a chaos agent, as a=
 dysfunctional president, as someone who made
bad decisions that weren=E2=80=99t aligned with their values. We can=E2=80=
=99t assume all that. We can=E2=80=99t rely on all that.=E2=80=9D

Smith=E2=80=99s perspective aligns with some of what I=E2=80=99ve heard fro=
m John Della Volpe, the director of the Harvard Youth Poll, who has done po=
lling for Snapchat, where I also work. In April, as part of his recent surv=
ey ( https://puck.news/rfk-jr-keeps-talking-young-voters-are-listening/?utm=
_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F10%2F24%29&utm_=
content=3DThe+Best+%26+The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%286%2F6%2F24%29&utm_med=
ium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=
 work on Gen Z voters, he noted that the younger members of Gen Z were in m=
iddle or high school when Trump launched his campaign in 2015. Now eligible=
 to cast ballots for the first time, many of them only started paying atten=
tion to politics a few years ago, maybe starting around the time of the Bid=
en inauguration or the Covid pandemic.

These voters are new
to politics in a way that would probably baffle adults who consider themsel=
ves longtime savants. A useful thought exercise would be to reflect back on=
 the first campaign you followed closely. Mine was the 2000 election, when =
I was at Georgetown, nerding out with other young strivers. I argued with m=
y classmates, watched a lot of Inside Politics and Crossfire, and cobbled t=
ogether money to pay for a Washington Post subscription. I was up late watc=
hing NBC News live when Tim Russert scribbled =E2=80=9CFlorida, Florida, Fl=
orida=E2=80=9D on that whiteboard. But the presidential election before tha=
t? I was in high school in 1996, and don=E2=80=99t remember much about poli=
tics back then at all, other than the names at the top of the ballot=E2=80=
=94and maybe Bob Dole falling off a stage somewhere? For a teenager, a few =
years is a lifetime.

It=E2=80=99s no wonder, then, that many of the Zoomers surveyed by Blueprin=
t don=E2=80=99t remember what went down during the
Trump presidency, or even the 2020 campaign, when Trump lied about a stolen=
 election and stoked the violence of January 6. =E2=80=9CThese things feel =
like a million years ago to them,=E2=80=9D Smith told me. Less than half of=
 young voters, for example, had heard of Trump infamously telling the Proud=
 Boys to =E2=80=9Cstand back and stand by=E2=80=9D in his first debate agai=
nst Biden. Only 40 percent of Gen Z voters had heard of Trump calling Georg=
ia=E2=80=99s secretary of state and demanding that he find the votes to ove=
rturn the state=E2=80=99s election results. And while 72 percent of young v=
oters had heard of Trump saying that the 2020 election was =E2=80=9Crigged=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cstolen,=E2=80=9D that still means more than a quarte=
r of young people remain oblivious to the skulduggery and violence which ma=
de headlines for the past four years and are now at the center of two crimi=
nal cases against the former president.

Even when reminded, or told for the first time, only 50 percent of the youn=
g voters surveyed said
they were =E2=80=9Cbothered=E2=80=9D by Trump=E2=80=99s claims that the ele=
ction was stolen. Only 46 percent were bothered by his meddling in Georgia,=
 and only 52 percent were bothered by his Charlottesville remarks.

The news here is that while most Americans remember a less chaotic, even at=
 times congenial, political landscape =E2=80=9Cbefore Trump,=E2=80=9D almos=
t no one in Gen Z does. For the kids, political havoc is the norm and the i=
dea of social trust is only academic. =E2=80=9CThe American political syste=
m has been on unfirm footing for an entire generation of American voters wh=
o are now reaching their late 20s and early 30s,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =E2=
=80=9CThere is very little loyalty to democracy as a concept. In the Trump =
era, which I=E2=80=99d say starts in 2015, it=E2=80=99s hard to look at tha=
t stretch of democracy and say, =E2=80=98Yeah, democracy works great for me=
=2E=E2=80=99 It isn=E2=80=99t yielding consis=
tently good outcomes, or at leas=
t outcomes that feel reasonable. There isn=E2=80=99t some automatic built-i=
n Schoolhouse
Rock loyalty to the democratic system that every American is born with. If =
all you know is the dysfunction, who cares if someone is undermining it?=E2=
=80=9D

The Values Wedge

There=E2=80=99s an ongoing debate over whether Biden should run against the=
 havoc of the Trump years under the banner of =E2=80=9CSaving Democracy,=E2=
=80=9D or run on his accomplishments and the issues (right now, mainly abor=
tion rights). It=E2=80=99s a false dichotomy. Biden can do both, of course,=
 and the technology exists to reach different audience clusters with differ=
ent messages. But the Blueprint poll should be a warning to the Resistance =
crowd demanding that Democrats Do Better! and build their campaigns around =
the idea of saving the republic from Trumpism. What matters to most voters =
right now=E2=80=94and this isn=E2=80=99t a shocker to anyone who can read a=
 poll=E2=80=94is the economy. The cost of living is far and away the bigges=
t concern among young voters. Rent, prices, gas, and debt are more salient =
to Gen Z than anything else. Especially dated outrage about Trump=E2=80=99s
rhetoric.

There are ways, Smith told me, for Biden to tie some of Trump=E2=80=99s pas=
t statements to an issues-based campaign message. After all, even if Biden =
is unpopular with young voters, they do align with him on the vast majority=
 of issues. Trump=E2=80=99s past remarks about race and gender, the poll fo=
und, are also the ones that Gen Z found the most bothersome. =E2=80=9CDrive=
 that values wedge,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s not about de=
mocracy. Drive that values wedge against Trump, that this guy is nothing li=
ke you. He doesn=E2=80=99t care about people like you, and the people he ca=
res about are the fabulously wealthy, ultra-rich, powerful white dudes just=
 like him, who have nothing for you. He=E2=80=99s going to look out for the=
m, and he's going to treat you like dirt. If you=E2=80=99re not white, if y=
ou=E2=80=99re a woman, he doesn=E2=80=99t care what happens to you. He does=
n=E2=80=99t care if you live or die or succeed or fail.=E2=80=9D

The lesson from the poll isn=E2=80=99t profound. It=E2=80=99s that Biden is
running for president in 2024. Not 2020, not 2016. The state of the economy=
=E2=80=94real or imagined, unfairly or not=E2=80=94belongs to him. And to l=
ean on the old maxim, elections are about the future and not the past. That=
=E2=80=99s especially true for impatient young Americans looking out on a f=
uture that doesn=E2=80=99t look very accommodating to them.

=E2=80=9CThese voters are not going to cast a negative vote against Trump o=
n the basis of the memory of how he was as president,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =
=E2=80=9CWe know they=E2=80=99re not going to cast a vote in defense of dem=
ocracy, because it=E2=80=99s not so clear that they=E2=80=99re interested i=
n defending democracy. So what can we get them to do? Cast a positive vote =
in favor of Biden. It=E2=80=99s not rocket science. Meet them where they ar=
e, on things like the economic pain they're experiencing. Acknowledge that =
this is not a great economy for young people. When you hear younger people =
who are undecided or leaning Trump or anything like that, it=E2=80=99s most=
ly an economic
argument of, Trump was good for the economy. With Trump, it can=E2=80=99t b=
e any worse than Biden, when things are so expensive. Their questions are n=
ot about democracy. Their questions are: Will I ever not need roommates?=E2=
=80=9D

