          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">No matter your part=
isan affiliation, you likely remember the scandals that defined Trump=E2=80=
=99s first campaign for president and his presidency: the Muslim ban; the <=
i>Access Hollywood</i> tape; the claims that Mexican migrants are murderers=
 and rapists; the dismissal of servicemen who died in war as  =E2=80=9Close=
rs=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Csuckers.=E2=80=9D That story about Trump calling H=
aiti and African nations =E2=80=9Cshithole countries.=E2=80=9D And so on. T=
hese low points will be in Trump=E2=80=99s obituary. MSNBC has been talking=
 about them in primetime for almost a decade.<br/><br/>But in a <u><a href=
=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0d=
RQk05SV9SaFhwTHp1cl92bnJnRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9ibHVlcHJpbnQyMDI0LmNvbS=
9hbmFseXNpcy90cnVtcC1zdGF0ZW1lbnRzLXlvdXRoLXBvbGwvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQ=
mVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODYlMkYxMCUyRjI0JTI5XHUw=
MDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUys=
lMjg2JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAwMjZ1dG1fc2=
91cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwiaW50Z=
XJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo5MjEyMzh9/d8bae6efc29dc05=
05678a9bd3ea829a6dc6598b3bbb644b2cdca93417777e902" style=3D"color:#d40000;t=
ext-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">survey of registered vo=
ters</a></u> between
the ages of 18 and 30, Blueprint found that multitudes of young people in A=
merica have never even <i>heard</i> of these Trump comments. Only 42 percen=
t of young voters were aware of Trump disparaging <b>John</b> <b>McCain</b>=
 as =E2=80=9Cnot a war hero=E2=80=9D; the same low percentage had heard of =
Trump=E2=80=99s proposal for the =E2=80=9Ctotal and complete shutdown of Mu=
slims entering the United States.=E2=80=9D Likewise, a majority of young vo=
ters professed utter ignorance over Trump=E2=80=99s statement that there we=
re =E2=80=9Cvery fine people on both sides=E2=80=9D of the 2017 white supre=
macist march in Charlottesville, a moment the Biden campaign highlighted in=
 a digital ad back in March. <br/><br/>=E2=80=9CThe whole Trumpnesia lesson=
, to me, isn=E2=80=99t to go out and remind everyone of this stuff,=E2=80=
=9D said <b>Evan Ross Smith</b>, the lead pollster for Blueprint. =E2=80=9C=
The lesson is that you can=E2=80=99t rely on these voters having this bedro=
ck understanding of Trump as a chaos agent, as a dysfunctional president, a=
s someone who made
bad decisions that weren=E2=80=99t aligned with their values. We can=E2=80=
=99t assume all that. We can=E2=80=99t rely on all that.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>=
Smith=E2=80=99s perspective aligns with some of what I=E2=80=99ve heard fro=
m <b>John Della Volpe</b>, the director of the Harvard Youth Poll, who has =
done polling for Snapchat, where I also work. In April, as part of his <u><=
a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2Uktxc=
lJLZ0dRQk05SV9SaFhwTHp1cl92bnJnRT0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvcmZr=
LWpyLWtlZXBzLXRhbGtpbmcteW91bmctdm90ZXJzLWFyZS1saXN0ZW5pbmcvP3V0bV9jYW1wYWl=
nbj1UaGUrQmVzdCslMjYrVGhlK0JyaWdodGVzdCstK1NVQlNDUklCRVJTKyUyODYlMkYxMCUyRj=
I0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX2NvbnRlbnQ9VGhlK0Jlc3QrJTI2K1RoZStCcmlnaHRlc3QrLStTVUJTQ=
1JJQkVSUyslMjg2JTJGNiUyRjI0JTI5XHUwMDI2dXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbF9hY3Rpb25cdTAw=
MjZ1dG1fc291cmNlPWN1c3RvbWVyLmlvXHUwMDI2dXRtX3Rlcm09ZjZjNjA2MTdkYTQyYWJkMTJ=
hIiwiaW50ZXJuYWwiOiJmNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJsaW5rX2lkIjo4NjMxNjB9/7302d=
9059e5121f29ea56be1f930e212b1641d3c238707d34ed646d10126efe5" style=3D"color=
:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">recent survey=
</a></u> work on Gen Z voters, he noted that the younger members of Gen Z w=
ere in middle or high school when Trump launched his campaign in 2015. Now =
eligible to cast ballots for the first time, many of them only started payi=
ng attention to politics a few years ago, maybe starting around the time of=
 the Biden inauguration or the Covid pandemic. <br/><br/>These voters are n=
ew
to politics in a way that would probably baffle adults who consider themsel=
ves longtime savants. A useful thought exercise would be to reflect back on=
 the first campaign you followed closely. Mine was the 2000 election, when =
I was at Georgetown, nerding out with other young strivers. I argued with m=
y classmates, watched a lot of <i>Inside Politics</i> and <i>Crossfire</i>,=
 and cobbled together money to pay for a <i>Washington Post</i> subscriptio=
n. I was up late watching NBC News live when <b>Tim</b> <b>Russert</b> scri=
bbled =E2=80=9CFlorida, Florida, Florida=E2=80=9D on that whiteboard. But t=
he presidential election before that? I was in high school in 1996, and don=
=E2=80=99t remember much about politics back then at all, other than the na=
mes at the top of the ballot=E2=80=94and maybe <b>Bob Dole </b>falling off =
a stage somewhere? For a teenager, a few years is a lifetime. <br/><br/>It=
=E2=80=99s no wonder, then, that many of the Zoomers surveyed by Blueprint =
don=E2=80=99t remember what went down during the
Trump presidency, or even the 2020 campaign, when Trump lied about a stolen=
 election and stoked the violence of January 6. =E2=80=9CThese things feel =
like a million years ago to them,=E2=80=9D Smith told me. Less than half of=
 young voters, for example, had heard of Trump infamously telling the Proud=
 Boys to =E2=80=9Cstand back and stand by=E2=80=9D in his first debate agai=
nst Biden. Only 40 percent of Gen Z voters had heard of Trump calling Georg=
ia=E2=80=99s secretary of state and demanding that he find the votes to ove=
rturn the state=E2=80=99s election results. And while 72 percent of young v=
oters had heard of Trump saying that the 2020 election was =E2=80=9Crigged=
=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9Cstolen,=E2=80=9D that still means more than a quarte=
r of young people remain oblivious to the skulduggery and violence which ma=
de headlines for the past four years and are now at the center of two crimi=
nal cases against the former president.<br/><br/>Even when reminded, or tol=
d for the first time, only 50 percent of the young voters surveyed said
they were =E2=80=9Cbothered=E2=80=9D by Trump=E2=80=99s claims that the ele=
ction was stolen. Only 46 percent were bothered by his meddling in Georgia,=
 and only 52 percent were bothered by his Charlottesville remarks. <br/><br=
/>The news here is that while most Americans remember a less chaotic, even =
at times congenial, political landscape =E2=80=9Cbefore Trump,=E2=80=9D alm=
ost no one in Gen Z does. For the kids, political havoc is the norm and the=
 idea of social trust is only academic. =E2=80=9CThe American political sys=
tem has been on unfirm footing for an entire generation of American voters =
who are now reaching their late 20s and early 30s,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =E2=
=80=9CThere is very little loyalty to democracy as a concept. In the Trump =
era, which I=E2=80=99d say starts in 2015, it=E2=80=99s hard to look at tha=
t stretch of democracy and say, =E2=80=98Yeah, democracy works great for me=
=2E=E2=80=99 It isn=E2=80=99t yielding consis=
tently good outcomes, or at leas=
t outcomes that feel reasonable. There isn=E2=80=99t some automatic built-i=
n <i>Schoolhouse
Rock</i> loyalty to the democratic system that every American is born with.=
 If all you know is the dysfunction, who cares if someone is undermining it=
?=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
         </tr>
