          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">There=E2=80=99s an =
ongoing debate over whether Biden should run against the havoc of the Trump=
 years under the banner of =E2=80=9CSaving Democracy,=E2=80=9D or run on hi=
s accomplishments and the issues (right now, mainly abortion rights). It=E2=
=80=99s a false dichotomy. Biden can do both, of course, and the technology=
 exists to reach different audience clusters with different messages. But t=
he Blueprint poll should be a warning to the Resistance crowd demanding tha=
t Democrats <i>Do Better!</i> and build their campaigns around the idea of =
saving the republic from Trumpism. What matters to most voters right now=E2=
=80=94and this isn=E2=80=99t a shocker to anyone who can read a poll=E2=80=
=94is the economy. The cost of living is far and away the biggest concern a=
mong young voters. Rent, prices, gas, and debt are more salient to Gen Z th=
an anything else. Especially dated outrage about Trump=E2=80=99s
rhetoric.<br/><br/>There are ways, Smith told me, for Biden to tie some of =
Trump=E2=80=99s past statements to an issues-based campaign message. After =
all, even if Biden is unpopular with young voters, they do align with him o=
n the vast majority of issues. Trump=E2=80=99s past remarks about race and =
gender, the poll found, are also the ones that Gen Z found the most bothers=
ome. =E2=80=9CDrive that values wedge,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s not about democracy. Drive that values wedge against Trump, that th=
is guy is <i>nothing like you</i>. He doesn=E2=80=99t care about people lik=
e you, and the people he cares about are the fabulously wealthy, ultra-rich=
, powerful white dudes just like him, who have nothing for you. He=E2=80=99=
s going to look out for them, and he&#39;s going to treat you like dirt. If=
 you=E2=80=99re not white, if you=E2=80=99re a woman, he doesn=E2=80=99t ca=
re what happens to you. He doesn=E2=80=99t care if you live or die or succe=
ed or fail.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>The lesson from the poll isn=E2=80=99t profou=
nd. It=E2=80=99s that Biden is
running for president in 2024. Not 2020, not 2016. The state of the economy=
=E2=80=94real or imagined, unfairly or not=E2=80=94belongs to him. And to l=
ean on the old maxim, elections are about the future and not the past. That=
=E2=80=99s especially true for impatient young Americans looking out on a f=
uture that doesn=E2=80=99t look very accommodating to them. <br/><br/>=E2=
=80=9CThese voters are not going to cast a negative vote against Trump on t=
he basis of the memory of how he was as president,=E2=80=9D Smith said. =E2=
=80=9CWe know they=E2=80=99re not going to cast a vote in defense of democr=
acy, because it=E2=80=99s not so clear that they=E2=80=99re interested in d=
efending democracy. So what can we get them to do? Cast a positive vote in =
favor of Biden. It=E2=80=99s not rocket science. Meet them where they are, =
on things like the economic pain they&#39;re experiencing. Acknowledge that=
 this is not a great economy for young people. When you hear younger people=
 who are undecided or leaning Trump or anything like that, it=E2=80=99s mos=
tly an economic
argument of, <i>Trump was good for the economy. With Trump, it can=E2=80=99=
t be any worse than Biden, when things are so expensive. </i>Their question=
s are not about democracy. Their questions are: <i>Will I ever not need roo=
mmates?</i>=E2=80=9D<br/></td>
